              <h2>Frequently asked questions about West Virginia income tax</h2>

              <h3>Who has to file a West Virginia income tax return?</h3>
              <p>
                In general, you must file a West Virginia personal income tax
                return if:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You are a <strong>resident</strong> with income above the
                  state filing threshold, or
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are a
                  <strong>nonresident or part-year resident</strong> with West
                  Virginia–source income above the threshold.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Filing thresholds and rules can change, so always check the
                latest instructions on the
                <a
                  href="https://tax.wv.gov/individuals"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >WV Tax Department website</a
                >.
              </p>

              <h3>Does West Virginia tax Social Security benefits?</h3>
              <p>
                West Virginia has gradually reduced and, for many taxpayers,
                eliminated state tax on Social Security benefits, subject to
                income limits and phase-outs. Whether your benefits are taxable
                at the state level depends on your filing status and total
                income. Use the official instructions or a tax professional to
                determine your exact treatment.
              </p>

              <h3>Are there local income taxes in West Virginia?</h3>
              <p>
